*African American Vowel Shift: AAVE accents have traditionally resisted the [[cot-caught merger]] spreading nationwide, with {{sc|lot}}  pronounced {{IPA|[ä]}} and {{sc|thought}} traditionally pronounced {{IPA|[ɒɔ]}}, though now often {{IPA|[ɒ~ɔə]}}. Early 2000s research has shown that this resistance may continue to be reinforced by the fronting of {{sc|lot}}, linked through a [[chain shift]] of vowels to the  raising of the {{sc|trap}}, {{sc|dress}}, and perhaps {{sc|kit}} vowels. This chain shift is called the "African American Shift".<ref>Thomas, Erik. (2007). "Phonological and phonetic characteristics of AAVE". ''Language and Linguistics Compass''. 1. 450 - 475. 10.1111/j.1749-818X.2007.00029.x. p. 464.</ref>
*Reduction of certain [[diphthong]] forms to [[monophthong]]s, in particular, the {{sc|prize}} vowel {{IPA|/aɪ/}} is [[monophthong]]ized to {{IPA|[aː]}} except before [[voiceless consonant]]s (this is also found in most [[Southern American English|white Southern dialects]]). The vowel sound in {{sc|choice}} ({{IPA|/ɔɪ/}} in General American) is also monophthongized, especially before {{IPA|/l/}}, making ''boil'' indistinguishable from ''ball''.{{sfnp|Labov|1972|p=19}}
*[[Pin–pen merger]]: Before nasal consonants ({{IPA|/m/}}, {{IPA|/n/}}, and {{IPA|/ŋ/}}), {{sc|dress}} {{IPA|/ɛ/}} and {{sc|kit}}{{IPA|/ɪ/}} are both pronounced like {{IPA|[ɪ~ɪə]}}, making ''pen'' and ''pin'' [[homophone]]s.{{sfnp|Labov|1972|p=19}} This is also [[Phonological history of English high front vowels#Pin–pen merger|present in other dialects]], particularly of the South.
* The distinction between the {{sc|kit}} {{IPA|/ɪ/}} and {{sc|fleece}} {{IPA|/iː/}} vowels before [[liquid consonant]]s is frequently reduced or absent, making ''feel'' and ''fill'' homophones ([[Fill–feel merger|''fill''–''feel'' merger]]). {{IPAc-en|ʊər}} and {{IPAc-en|ɔːr}} also merge, making ''poor'' and ''pour'' homophones ([[Cure–force merger|''cure''–''force'' merger]]).{{sfnp|Labov|1972|p=19}}

===Consonants===
* Word-final devoicing of {{IPA|/b/}}, {{IPA|/d/}}, and {{IPA|/ɡ/}}, whereby, for example, ''cub'' sounds similar to ''cup'',{{sfnp|Green|2002|p=116}} though these words may retain the longer vowel pronunciations that typically precede voiced consonants.<ref>{{harvcoltxt|Bailey|Thomas|1998|p=89}}, citing {{Harvcoltxt|Wolfram|1994}}</ref> 
* AAVE speakers may not use the [[fricative consonant|fricatives]] {{IPA|[θ]}} (the ''th'' in "''th''in") and {{IPA|[ð]}} (the ''th'' of "''th'''en") that are present in other varieties of English. The phoneme's position in a word determine its exact sound.{{sfnp|Green|2002|pp=117–119}}
** Word-initially, {{IPAc-en|θ}} is normally the same as in other English dialects (so ''thin'' is {{IPA|[θɪn]}}); in other situations, it may [[th-fronting|move forward in the mouth]], going from [[Voiceless dental fricative|dental]] (with the tongue near the top teeth) to [[Voiceless labiodental fricative|labiodental]] (with the lower lip near the top teeth).
** Word-initially, {{IPAc-en|ð}} is {{IPA|[ð~d]}} (so ''this'' may be {{IPA|[dɪs]}}). In other situations, {{IPA|/ð/}} may move forward in the mouth, much like the aforementioned behavior of {{IPA|/θ/}}.
* Realization of final ''ng'' {{IPA|/ŋ/}}, the [[velar nasal]], as the [[alveolar nasal]] {{IPA|[n]}} in [[function word|function]] [[morpheme]]s and content morphemes with two or more syllables like ''-ing'', e.g. ''tripping'' is pronounced as ''trippin''. This change does not occur in one-syllable [[content word|content]] morphemes such as ''sing'', which is {{IPA|[sɪŋ]}} and not {{IPA|*[sɪn]}}. However, ''singing'' is {{IPA|[sɪŋɪn]}}. Other examples include ''wedding'' → {{IPA|[wɛɾɪn]}}, ''morning'' → {{IPA|[mɔɹnɪn]}}, ''nothing'' → {{IPA|[ˈnʌfɪn]}}. Realization of {{IPA|/ŋ/}} as {{IPA|[n]}} in these contexts is commonly found in many other English dialects.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Green|2002|pp=121–122}} although her examples are different.</ref>
* A marked feature of AAVE is final consonant cluster reduction. There are several phenomena that are similar but are governed by different grammatical rules.  This tendency has been used by creolists to compare AAVE to West African languages since such languages do not have final clusters.{{sfnp|Green|2002|p=107}}
** Final consonant clusters that are [[homorganic]]  (have the same [[place of articulation]]) and share the same [[voice (phonetics)|voicing]] are reduced. E.g. ''test'' is pronounced {{IPA|[tɛs]}} since {{IPA|/t/}} and {{IPA|/s/}} are both voiceless; ''hand'' is pronounced {{IPA|[hæn]}} (or, more narrowly {{IPA|[hɛən]}}), since {{IPA|/n/}} and {{IPA|/d/}} are both voiced; but ''pant'' is unchanged, as it contains both a voiced and a voiceless consonant in the cluster.{{sfnp|Rickford|1997b|p=??}} Note also that it is the plosive ({{IPA|/t/}} and {{IPA|/d/}}) in these examples that is lost rather than the fricative or nasal. Speakers may carry this declustered pronunciation when pluralizing so that the plural of test is {{IPA|[tɛsəs]}} rather than {{IPA|[tɛsts]}}.{{sfnp|Green|2002|pp=107–116}} The clusters {{IPA|/ft/}}, {{IPA|/md/}}, are also affected.{{sfnp|Labov|1972|p=15}}
** More often, word-final {{IPA|/sp/}}, {{IPA|/st/}}, and {{IPA|/sk/}} are reduced, again with the final element being deleted rather than the former.{{sfnp|Labov|1972|pp=15–16}}
** For younger speakers, {{IPA|/skr/}} also occurs in words that other varieties of English have {{IPA|/str/}} so that, for example, ''street'' is pronounced {{IPA|[skrit]}}.{{sfnp|Green|2002|p=123}}
** Clusters ending in {{IPA|/s/}} or {{IPA|/z/}} exhibit variation in whether the first or second element is deleted.{{sfnp|Labov|1972|pp=17–18}}
* Similarly, final consonants may be deleted (although there is a great deal of variation between speakers in this regard). Most often, {{IPA|/t/}} and {{IPA|/d/}} are deleted. As with other dialects of English, final {{IPA|/t/}} and {{IPA|/k/}} may reduce to a [[glottal stop]]. Nasal consonants may be lost while nasalization of the vowel is retained (e.g., ''find'' may be pronounced {{IPA|[fãː]}}). More rarely, {{IPA|/s/}} and {{IPA|/z/}} may also be deleted.{{sfnp|Labov|1972|pp=18–19}}
* Use of [[Phonological history of English consonant clusters#S-cluster metathesis|metathesized]] forms like ''aks'' for "ask"<ref>See {{Harvcoltxt|Baugh|2000|pp=92–94}} on "aks" and metathesis, on the frequency with which "aks" is brought up by those who ridicule AAVE (e.g.{{Harvcoltxt|Cosby|1997}}), and on the linguistic or cognitive abilities of a speaker of another variety of English who would take "aks" to mean "axe" in a context that in another variety would probably call for "ask".</ref> or ''graps'' for "grasp".
* General [[rhotic and non-rhotic accents|non-rhotic]] behavior, in which the [[rhotic consonant]] {{IPA|/r/}} is typically dropped when not followed by a vowel; it may also manifest as an unstressed {{IPA|[ə]}} or the lengthening of the preceding vowel.{{sfnp|Green|2002|pp=119–121}} Intervocalic {{IPA|/r/}} may also be dropped, e.g. General American ''story'' ({{IPA|[stɔri]}}) can be pronounced {{IPA|[stɔ.i]}}, though this doesn't occur across morpheme boundaries.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Green|2002|p=121}}, citing {{Harvcoltxt|Wolfram|Fasold|1974|p=140}}</ref> {{IPA|/r/}} may also be deleted between a consonant and a back rounded vowel, especially in words like ''throw'', ''throat'', and ''through''.{{sfnp|Labov|1972|p=14}}
**The level of AAVE rhoticity is likely somewhat correlated with the rhoticity of white speakers in a given region; in 1960s research, AAVE accents tended to be mostly non-rhotic in Detroit, whose white speakers are rhotic, but completely non-rhotic in New York City, whose white speakers are also often non-rhotic.<ref>Wolfram, Walt; Kohn, Mary E. (forthcoming). "[https://www.academia.edu/20295897/The_Regional_Development_of_African_American_Language The regional development of African American Language]". In Sonja Lanehart, Lisa Green, and Jennifer Bloomquist (eds.), ''The Oxford Handbook on African American Language''. Oxford: Oxford University Press. p. 147.</ref>
* {{IPA|/l/}} is often vocalized in patterns similar to that of {{IPA|/r/}} (though never between vowels){{sfnp|Green|2002|p=121}} and, in combination with cluster simplification (see above), can make homophones of ''toll'' and ''toe'', ''fault'' and ''fought'', and ''tool'' and ''too''. Homonymy may be reduced by vowel lengthening and by an off-glide {{IPA|[ɤ]}}.{{sfnp|Labov|1972|pp=14–15}}

=== "Deep" phonology ===
[[John McWhorter]] discusses an accent [[Post-creole continuum#Other examples|continuum]] from "a 'deep' Black English through a 'light' Black English to standard English," saying the sounds on this continuum may vary from one African American speaker to the next or even in a single speaker from one situational context to the next.{{sfnp|McWhorter|2001|pp=146}} McWhorter regards the following as rarer features, characteristic only of a deep Black English but which speakers of light Black English may occasionally "dip into for humorous or emotive effect":{{sfnp|McWhorter|2001|pp=146–7}}
* Lowering of {{IPA|/ɪ/}} before {{IPA|/ŋ/}}, causing pronunciations such as {{IPA|[θɛŋ~θæŋ]}} for ''thing'' (sounding something like ''thang'').{{sfnp|Green|2002|p=123}}
* Word-medially and word-finally, pronouncing {{IPA|/θ/}} as {{IPA|[f]}} (so {{IPA|[mʌmf]}} for ''month'' and {{IPA|[mæɔf]}} for ''mouth''), and {{IPA|/ð/}} as {{IPA|[v]}} (so {{IPA|[smuːv]}} for ''smooth'' and {{IPA|[ɹævə(ɹ)]}} for ''rather''.{{sfnp|McWhorter|2001|pp=148}} This is called [[Th-fronting|''th''-fronting]]. Word-initially, {{IPAc-en|ð}} is {{IPA|[d]}} (so ''those'' and ''doze'' sound nearly identical). This is called [[th-stopping|''th''-stopping]]. In other words, the tongue fully touches the top teeth.
*Glide deletion ([[monophthong]]ization) of all instances of {{IPAc-en|aɪ}}, universally, resulting in {{IPA|[aː~äː]}} (so that, for example, even ''rice'' may sound like ''rahs''.)
*Full gliding ([[diphthongization]]) of {{IPAc-en|ɪ}}, resulting in {{IPA|[iə]}} (so that ''win'' may sound like ''wee-un'').
*[[Raising (phonology)|Raising]] and fronting of the vowel {{IPAc-en|ʌ}} of words like ''strut, mud, tough'', etc. to something like {{IPA|[ɜː~əː]}}.

==Grammar==
=== Tense and aspect ===
Although AAVE does not necessarily have the [[preterite|simple past-tense]] marker of other English varieties (that is, the ''-ed'' of "work''ed''"), it does have an optional tense system with at least four aspects of the past tense and two aspects of the future tense.{{sfnp|Fickett|1972|pp=17–18}}

{| class="wikitable"
|-
|+Phases/Tenses of AAVE{{sfnp|Fickett|1972|p=19}}
!colspan=2| Phase
! Example
|-align=center
!rowspan=4|Past
!Pre-recent
| ''I been bought it''
|-align=center
!Recent
| ''I done buy it''{{Ref|dən|a}}
|-align=center
! Pre-present
| ''I did buy it''
|-align=center
! Past Inceptive
| ''I do buy it''
|-align=center
! colspan=2|Present
| ''I be buying it''
|-align=center
!rowspan=3|Future
! Immediate
| ''I'm a-buy it''
|-align=center
! Post-immediate
|  ''I'm a-gonna buy it''
|-align=center
! Indefinite future
| ''I gonna buy it''
|}
{{note|dən|a}}Syntactically, ''I bought it'' is grammatical, but ''done'' (always unstressed, pronounced as /dən/) is used to emphasize the completed nature of the action.{{sfnp|Green|2002|pp=60–62}}

As phase auxiliary verbs, ''been'' and ''done'' must occur as the first auxiliary; when they occur as the second, they carry additional [[grammatical aspect|aspects]]:{{sfnp|Fickett|1972|p=19}}
: ''He been done work'' means "he finished work a long time ago".
: ''He done been work'' means "until recently, he worked over a long period of time".

The latter example shows one of the most distinctive features of AAVE: the use of ''be'' to indicate that performance of the verb is of a habitual nature. In most other American English dialects, this can only be expressed unambiguously by using adverbs such as ''usually''.<ref>Aspectual ''be'': {{Harvcoltxt|Green|2002|pp=47–54}}</ref>

This aspect-marking form of ''been'' or BIN<ref>In order to distinguish the stressed and unstressed forms, which carry different meaning, linguists often write the stressed version as BIN</ref> is stressed and semantically distinct from the unstressed form: ''She BIN running'' ('She has been running for a long time') and ''She been running'' ('She has been running').{{sfnp|Green|2002|pp=54–55}}  This aspect has been given several names, including ''perfect phase'', ''remote past'', and ''remote phase'' (this article uses the third).{{sfnp|Rickford|1999|p=??}}  As shown above, ''been'' places action in the distant past. However, when ''been'' is used with [[stative verb]]s or [[gerund]] forms, ''been'' shows that the action began in the distant past and that it is continuing now. {{Harvcoltxt|Rickford|1999}} suggests that a better translation when used with stative verbs is "for a long time". For instance, in response to "I like your new dress", one might hear ''Oh, I been had this dress'', meaning that the speaker has had the dress for a long time and that it isn't new.{{sfnp|Rickford|1999|p=??}}

To see the difference between the simple past and the gerund when used with ''been'', consider the following expressions:
: ''I been bought her clothes'' means "I bought her clothes a long time ago".
: ''I been buying her clothes'' means "I've been buying her clothes for a long time".

