{{Infobox NRHP | name = Potomac Palisades Site | nrhp_type = | image = Potomac palisades.jpg | caption = Mound in the unexcavated site | location = Overlooking the [[Potomac River]] at MacArthur Boulevard and Foxhall Road | nearest_city= [[Washington, D.C.]] | coordinates = {{coord|38|54|21|N|77|4|52|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = United States Washington, D.C. | architect = | architecture = | added = April 15, 1982 | area = {{convert|1|acre}} | governing_body = Federal | refnum = 82001714<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }}
The '''Potomac Palisades Site''' is an [[archaeological site]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]. Measuring approximately {{convert|1|acre}} in area,<ref name=nris /> the site lies near the intersection of MacArthur Boulevard and Foxhall Road,<ref name=pmop>Artemel, Janice G., et al. "[http://www.pmop.org/documents/prelimsurveypp.pdf Preliminary Archaeological Survey 23 Recreation Facilities Washington DC.]" [[Washington, D.C.]]: Engineering-Science for the District of Columbia Department of Recreation, 1984-09.</ref>{{rp|4}} along the [[Potomac River]].<ref name=afrh>Greenhorne & O'Mara. "[http://www.afrhdevelopment.com/pdf/AFRHPhaseIA-Archeological%20ReportOct2004.pdf Phase IA Archeological Assessment of the Armed Forces Retirement Home] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111115194853/http://www.afrhdevelopment.com/pdf/AFRHPhaseIA-Archeological%20ReportOct2004.pdf |date=2011-11-15 }}." [[Washington, D.C.]]: Greenhorne & O'Mara for the Armed Forces Retirement Home, 2004-10, 14.</ref> It is one of many archaeological sites located in the present-day [[The Palisades, Washington, D.C.|Potomac Palisades]];<ref name=pmop />{{rp|4}} a 1984 [[Archaeological field survey|field survey]] revealed evidence that supported earlier ideas of the archaeological richness of the northern bank of the Potomac in this area.<ref name=pmop />{{rp|8}}
Among the [[artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]] found during [[Excavation (archaeology)|excavation]] at the site is a triangle-shaped [[projectile point]].<ref name=afrh /> The primary use of the site appears to have been during the [[Archaic period in the Americas|Late Archaic period]], during which time it was heavily used as a [[Stone tool|lithic]] workshop.<ref name=pmop />{{rp|4}} In recognition of its archaeological value, the Potomac Palisades Site was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1982.<ref name=nris />
